# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uwp-apps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] A **progressive web application** (**PWA**), or **progressive web app**, is a type of web app that can be installed on a device as a standalone application.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] PWAs are installed using the offline cache of the device's web browser.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] PWAs were introduced from 2016 as an alternative to native (device-specific) applications, with the advantage that they do not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] They can be used on a range of different systems, including desktop and mobile devices.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Publishing the app to digital distribution systems, such as the Apple App Store, Google Play, or the Microsoft Store on Windows, is optional.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Because a PWA is delivered in the form of a webpage or website built using common web technologies including HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and WebAssembly, it can work on any platform with a PWA-compatible browser.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] As of 2025, PWA features are supported to varying degrees by Google Chrome, Apple Safari, Brave, Firefox for Android, Microsoft Edge, and Firefox for Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] At Apple's Worldwide Developers Conference in 2007, Steve Jobs announced that the iPhone would "run applications created with Web 2.0 Internet standards".
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] No software development kit (SDK) was required, and the apps would be fully integrated into the device through the Safari browser engine.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] This model was later switched to the App Store, as a means of appeasing frustrated developers.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] In October 2007 Jobs announced that an SDK would be launched the following year.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] As a result, although Apple continued to support web apps, the vast majority of iOS applications shifted toward the App Store.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Beginning in the early 2010s dynamic web pages allowed web technologies to be used to create interactive web applications.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Responsive web design, and the screen-size flexibility it provides have made PWA development more accessible.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Continued enhancements to HTML, CSS, and JavaScript allowed web applications to incorporate greater levels of interactivity, making native-like experiences possible on a website.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] It was intended to be an open-source operating system for running web apps as native apps on mobile devices.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Firefox OS was based on the Gecko rendering engine with a user interface called Gaia, written in HTML5.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] The development of Firefox OS ended in 2016, and the project was completely discontinued in 2017, although a fork of Firefox OS was used as the basis of KaiOS, a feature phone platform.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Google then put significant efforts into promoting PWA development for Android.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Firefox introduced support for service workers in 2016, and Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari followed in 2018, making service workers available on all major systems.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] By 2019, PWAs were supported by desktop versions of some browsers, including Microsoft Edge (on Windows) and Google Chrome (on Windows, macOS, ChromeOS, and Linux).
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] In December 2020, Firefox for desktop abandoned the implementation of PWAs (specifically, removed the prototype "site-specific browser" configuration that had been available as an experimental feature).
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] A Firefox architect noted: "The signal I hope we are sending is that PWA support is not coming to desktop Firefox anytime soon." Mozilla supports PWAs on Android and plans to keep supporting it.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Firefox version 143.0, released in September 2025, added support for PWA on Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps are all designed to work on any browser that is compliant with the appropriate web standards.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] As with other cross-platform solutions, the goal is to help developers build cross-platform apps more easily than they would with native apps.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Progressive web apps employ the progressive enhancement web development strategy.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Some progressive web apps use an architectural approach called the App Shell Model.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] In this model, service workers store the Basic User Interface or "shell" of the responsive web design web application in the browser's offline cache.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] This model allows for PWAs to maintain native-like use with or without web connectivity.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] This can improve loading time, by providing an *initial static frame*, a layout or architecture into which content can be loaded progressively as well as dynamically.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] There are many technologies commonly used to create progressive web apps.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] A web application is considered a PWA if it satisfies the installation criteria, thus can work offline and can be added to the device's home screen.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] To meet this definition, all PWAs require at minimum a manifest and a service worker.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Other technologies may be used to store data, communicate with servers or execute code.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] This metadata is crucial for an app to be added to a home screen or otherwise listed alongside native apps.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] iOS Safari partially implements manifests, while most of the PWA metadata can be defined via Apple-specific extensions to the meta tags.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] These tags allow developers to enable full-screen display, define icons and splash screens, and specify a name for the application.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] A service worker is a web worker that implements a programmable network proxy that can respond to web/HTTP requests from the main document.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] It is able to check the availability of a remote server, cache content when that server is available, and serve that content to the document later.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Service workers, like any other web workers, work separately from the main document context.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Service workers can handle push notifications and synchronize data in the background, cache or retrieve resource requests, intercept network requests and receive centralized updates independently of the document that registered them, even when that document is not loaded.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Service workers go through a three-step lifecycle of Registration, Installation and Activation.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Registration involves telling the browser the location of the service worker in preparation for installation.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Installation occurs when there is no service worker installed in the browser for the web app, or if there is an update to the service worker.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Activation occurs when all of the PWA's pages are closed, so that there is no conflict between the previous version and the updated one.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] The lifecycle also helps maintain consistency when switching among versions of a service worker since only a single service worker can be active for a domain.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] WebAssembly allows precompiled code to run in a web browser, at near-native speed.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Thus, libraries written in languages such as C can be added to web apps.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Announced in 2015 and first released in March 2017, WebAssembly became a W3C recommendation on December 5, 2019 and it received the Programming Languages Software Award from ACM SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] is a WHATWG standard API that enables key–value storage in modern browsers.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] (that enables storage that persists across sessions).
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] is a W3C standard database API available in all major browsers.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] objects and any structures representable as a string.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] providing additional constructs around it.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] In 2017, Twitter released Twitter Lite, a PWA alternative to the official native Android and iOS apps.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] According to Twitter, Twitter Lite consumed only 1–3% of the size of the native apps.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Starbucks provides a PWA that is 99.84% smaller than its equivalent iOS app.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] After deploying its PWA, Starbucks doubled the number of online orders, with desktop users ordering at about the same rate as mobile app users.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] A 2018 review published by Forbes, found that users of Pinterest's PWA spent 40% more time on the site compared to the previous mobile website.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Ad revenue rates also increased by 44%, and core engagements by 60%.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Flipkart saw 60% of customers who had uninstalled their native app return to use the Flipkart PWA.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Lancôme saw an 84% decrease in time until the page is interactive, leading to a 17% increase in conversions and a 53% increase in mobile sessions on iOS with their PWA.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Since a PWA does not require separate bundling or distribution for different platforms and is available to users via the web, it is not necessary for developers to release it over digital distribution systems like the Apple App Store, Google Play, Microsoft Store, or Samsung Galaxy Store.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] The major app stores support the publication of PWAs to varying degrees.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Google Play, Microsoft Store, and Samsung Galaxy Store support PWAs, but Apple App Store does not.
[src:uwp-apps/progressive-web-app] Microsoft Store publishes some qualifying PWAs automatically (even without app authors' requests) after discovering them via Bing indexing.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] , on a computer screen (left) and on a mobile phone screen (right).
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] The elements rearrange themselves into a more mobile friendly layout.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design became more important as users of mobile devices came to account for the majority of website visitors.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] In 2015, for instance, Google announced Mobilegeddon and started to boost the page ranking of mobile-friendly sites when searching from a mobile device.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design is an example of user interface plasticity.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Luke Wroblewski has summarized some of the responsive and mobile design challenges and created a catalog of multi-device layout patterns.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] He suggested that, compared with a simple responsive web design approach, device experience or RESS (responsive web design with server-side components) approaches can provide a user experience that is better optimized for mobile devices.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Server-side CSS generator implementation of stylesheet languages like Sass can be part of such an approach.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Google has recommended responsive design for smartphone websites over other approaches.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Although many publishers have implemented responsive designs, one challenge for responsive design adoption was that some banner advertisements and videos were not fluid.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] However, search advertising and (banner) display advertising came to support specific device platform targeting and different advertisement size formats for desktop, smartphone, and basic mobile devices.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Different landing page URLs have been used for different platforms, or Ajax has been used to display different advertisement variants on a page.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] CSS tables permitted hybrid fixed and fluid layouts.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] There have been many ways of validating and testing responsive web designs, ranging from mobile site validators and mobile emulators to simultaneous testing tools like Adobe Edge Inspect.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] The Chrome, Firefox and Safari browsers and developer tools have offered responsive design viewport resizing tools, as do third parties.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] The W3C specification of HTML+ stated that websites have to be rendered according to the user preferences.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] The customization of web page layout was lacking however.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Many web developers resorted to ordinary HTML tables as a way to customize the layout and bring some basic responsiveness to their websites at the same time.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Limited browser capabilities meant that for Internet Explorer, the layout could adapt dynamically in the browser whereas, for Netscape, the page had to be reloaded from the server when resized.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Cameron Adams created a demonstration in 2004.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] By 2008, a number of related terms such as "flexible", "liquid", "fluid", and "elastic" were being used to describe layouts.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] CSS3 media queries were almost ready for prime time in late 2008/early 2009.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Ethan Marcotte coined the term *responsive web design*—and defined it to mean fluid grid / flexible images / media queries—in a May 2010 article in *A List Apart*.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] He described the theory and practice of responsive web design in his brief 2011 book titled *Responsive Web Design*.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Responsive design was listed as #2 in Top Web Design Trends for 2012 by .net magazine after progressive enhancement at #1.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] Mashable called 2013 the Year of Responsive Web Design.
[src:uwp-apps/responsive-web-design] User interface plasticity is the capacity of a user interface to withstand variations of both the system's physical characteristics and the environment while preserving usability.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:uwp-apps/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] UWP does not target non-Microsoft systems.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Microsoft's solution for other platforms is .NET MAUI (previously "Xamarin.Forms"), an open-source API created by Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary since 2016.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Community solutions also exist for non-targeted platforms, such as Uno Platform.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] UWP is a part of Windows 10, Windows 10 Mobile and Windows 11.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] UWP apps do not run on earlier Windows versions.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Apps that are capable of implementing this platform are natively developed using Visual Studio 2015, Visual Studio 2017, Visual Studio 2019, or Visual Studio 2022.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Older Metro-style apps for Windows 8.1, Windows Phone 8.1, or for both (universal 8.1) need modifications to migrate to UWP.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Some Windows platform features in later versions have been exclusive to UWP and software specifically packaged for it, and are not usable in other architectures such as the existing WinAPI, WPF, and Windows Forms.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] However, as of 2019, Microsoft has taken steps to increase the parity between these application platforms and make UWP features usable inside non-UWP software.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Microsoft introduced XAML Islands (a method for embedding UWP controls and widgets into non-UWP software) as part of the Windows 10 May 2019 update, and stated that it would also allow UWP functions and Windows Runtime components to be invoked within non-packaged software.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] UWP Bridges translate calls in other application programming interfaces (APIs) to the UWP interface, so that applications written in these APIs would run on UWP.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Two bridges are announced during the 2015 Build keynote for Android and iOS apps to be ported to Windows 10 Mobile.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Until January 2022, Microsoft maintained support for bridges for Windows desktop apps, progressive web apps, Microsoft Silverlight, and iOS's Cocoa Touch API.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] This "WinObjC" project is open source on GitHub.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] It contains code from various existing implementations of Cocoa Touch like Cocotron and GNUstep as well as Microsoft's own code that implements iOS frameworks using UWP methods.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] It uses a version of the LLVM clang compiler.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] In February 2016, Microsoft announced that it had ceased development on Windows Bridge for Android, citing redundancies due to iOS already being a primary platform for multi-platform development, and that Windows Bridge for iOS produced native code and did not require an OS-level emulator.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Instead, Microsoft encouraged the use of C# for multi-platform app development using tools from Xamarin, which they had acquired prior to the announcement.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] In 2021, Microsoft allowed Windows 11 to run Android apps with an OS-level emulator and allowed apps to be installed in the store.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] UWP provides an application model based upon its CoreApplication class and the Windows Runtime (WinRT).
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Universal Windows apps that are created using the UWP no longer indicate having been written for a specific OS in their manifest build; instead, they target one or more device families, such as a PC, smartphone, tablet, or Xbox One, using Universal Windows Platform Bridges.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] These extensions allow the app to automatically utilize the capabilities that are available to the particular device it is currently running on.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] A universal app may run on either a mobile phone or a tablet and provide suitable experiences on each.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] A universal app running on a smartphone may start behaving the way it would if it were running on a PC when the phone is connected to a desktop computer or a suitable docking station.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Games developed for UWP are subject to technical restrictions, including incompatibility with multi-video card setups, difficulties modding the game, overlays for gameplay-oriented chat clients, or key binding managers.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] UWP will only support DirectX 11.1 or later, so games built on older DirectX versions will not work.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Epic Games founder Tim Sweeney criticized UWP for being a walled garden, since by default UWP software may only be published and installed via Windows Store, requiring changes in system settings to enable the installation of external software (similarly to Android).
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Additionally, certain operating system features are exclusive to UWP and cannot be used in non-UWP software such as most video games.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] As such, Sweeney argued that end-users should be able to download UWP software and install it in the same manner as non-UWP software.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Windows VP Kevin Gallo addressed Sweeney's concerns, stating that "in the Windows 10 November Update, we enabled people to easily side-load apps by default, with no UX required.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] We want to make Windows the best development platform regardless of technologies used, and offer tools to help developers with existing code bases of HTML/JavaScript, .NET and Win32, C++ and Objective-C bring their code to Windows, and integrate UWP capabilities.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] In a live interview with *Giant Bomb* during its E3 2016 coverage, Spencer defended the mixed reception of its UWP-exclusive releases, stating that "they all haven't gone swimmingly.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] Some of them have gone well", and that "there's still definitely concern that UWP and our store are somehow linked in a way that is nefarious.
[src:uwp-apps/universal-windows-platform] The end result is better for gamers." Spencer also stated that he was a friend of Sweeney and had been in frequent contact with him.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The **Windows API**, informally **WinAPI**, is the foundational application programming interface (API) that allows a computer program to access the features of the Microsoft Windows operating system in which the program is running.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Programs typically access this API using system libraries, which are shared libraries.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Each major version of the Windows API has a distinct name that identifies a compatibility aspect of that version.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] For example, Win32 is the major version of Windows API that runs on 32-bit systems.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The name, Windows API, collectively refers to all versions of this capability of Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Microsoft provides developer support via a software development kit, Microsoft Windows SDK, which includes documentation and tools for building software based on the Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] This section lists notable services provided by the Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Base services include features such as the file system, devices, processes, threads, and error handling.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] These functions reside in kernel.exe, krnl286.exe or krnl386.exe files on 16-bit Windows, and kernel32.dll and KernelBase.dll on 32 and 64 bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] These files reside in the folder \Windows\System32 on all versions of Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Advanced services include features beyond the kernel like the Windows registry, shutdown/restart the system (or abort), start/stop/create a Windows service, manage user accounts.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] These functions reside in advapi32.dll and advapires32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Graphics Device Interface (GDI) component provides features to output graphics content to monitors, printers, and other output devices.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] It resides in gdi.exe on 16-bit Windows, and gdi32.dll on 32-bit Windows in user-mode.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Kernel-mode GDI support is provided by `win32k.sys` which communicates directly with the graphics driver.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The User Interface component provides features to create and manage screen windows and most basic controls, such as buttons and scrollbars, receive mouse and keyboard input, and other functions associated with the graphical user interface (GUI) part of Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] This functional unit resides in user.exe on 16-bit Windows, and user32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Since Windows XP versions, the basic controls reside in comctl32.dll, together with the common controls (Common Control Library).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Common Dialog Box Library provides standard dialog boxes to open and save files, choose color and font, etc.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The library resides in a file called commdlg.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comdlg32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] It is grouped under the *User Interface* category of the API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Common Control Library provides access to advanced user interface controls, including things like status bars, progress bars, toolbars and tabs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The library resides in a DLL file called commctrl.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comctl32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Windows Shell component provides access to the operating system shell.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The component resides in shell.dll on 16-bit Windows, and shell32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Shell Lightweight Utility Functions are in shlwapi.dll.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Network Services provide access to the various networking abilities of the operating system.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Its subcomponents include NetBIOS, Winsock, NetDDE, remote procedure call (RPC) and many more.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] This component resides in netapi32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Internet Explorer (IE) web browser exposes APIs and as such could be considered part of the Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] IE has been included with the operating system since Windows 95 OSR2 and has provided web-related services to applications since Windows 98.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Windows API is a C language-based API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Functions and data structures are consumable via C syntax by including windows.h, but the API can be consumed via any programming language that can inter-operate with the API data structures and calling conventions for function calls and callbacks.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Of note, the implementation of API functions has been developed in several languages other than C.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Despite the fact that C is not an object-oriented programming (OOP) language, the Windows API is somewhat object-oriented due to its use of handles.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Various other technologies from Microsoft and others make this object-oriented aspect more apparent by using an OOP language such as C++ — see Microsoft Foundation Class Library (MFC), Visual Component Library (VCL), GDI+.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Of note, Windows 8 provides the Windows API and the WinRT API, which is implemented in C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Windows.pas is a Delphi unit that exposes the features of Windows API – the Pascal equivalent of windows.h.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Many Microsoft technologies use the Windows API—as most software running on Windows does.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] As middle-ware between Windows API and an application, the following technologies provide some access to Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Some technologies are described as wrapping Windows API, but this is debatable since they don't provide or expose all of the capabilities of Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Although almost all Windows programs use the Windows API, on the Windows NT line of operating systems, programs that start early in the Windows startup process use the Native API instead.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Windows API has always exposed a large part of the underlying structure of the Windows systems to programmers.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] This had the advantage of giving them much flexibility and power over their applications, but also creates great responsibility in how applications handle various low-level, sometimes tedious, operations that are associated with a graphical user interface.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] For example, a beginning C programmer will often write the simple "hello world" as their first assignment.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The working part of the program is only a single printf line within the main subroutine.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Charles Petzold, who wrote several books about programming for the Windows API, said: "The original hello world program in the Windows 1.0 SDK was a bit of a scandal.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] HELLO.C was about 150 lines long, and the HELLO.RC resource script had another 20 or so more lines.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] (...) Veteran programmers often curled up in horror or laughter when encountering the Windows hello-world program." Petzold explains that while it was the first Windows sample programs developers were introduced to, it was quite "fancy" and more complex than needed.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Tired of people ridiculing the length of the sample, he eventually reduced it to a simple MessageBox call.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Over the years, various changes and additions were made to Windows systems, and the Windows API changed and grew to reflect this.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Windows API for Windows 1.0 supported fewer than 450 function calls, whereas modern versions of the Windows API support thousands.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] However, in general, the interface remained fairly consistent, and an old Windows 1.0 application will still look familiar to a programmer who is used to the modern Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Microsoft has made an effort to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] To achieve this, when developing new versions of Windows, Microsoft sometimes implemented workarounds to allow compatibility with third-party software that used the prior version in an undocumented or even inadvisable way.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Raymond Chen, a Microsoft developer who works on the Windows API, has said: "I could probably write for months solely about bad things apps do and what we had to do to get them to work again (often in spite of themselves).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Which is why I get particularly furious when people accuse Microsoft of maliciously breaking applications during OS upgrades.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] One of the largest changes to the Windows API was the transition from Win16 (shipped in Windows 3.1 and older) to Win32 (Windows NT and Windows 95 and up).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] While Win32 was originally introduced with Windows NT 3.1 and Win32s allowed use of a Win32 subset before Windows 95, it was not until Windows 95 that widespread porting of applications to Win32 began.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] To ease the transition, in Windows 95, for developers outside and inside Microsoft, a complex scheme of API thunks was used that could allow 32-bit code to call into 16-bit code (for most of Win16 APIs) and vice versa.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] *Flat thunks* allowed 32-bit code to call into 16-bit libraries, and the scheme was used extensively inside Windows 95's libraries to avoid porting the whole OS to Win32 in one batch.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] In Windows NT, the OS was pure 32-bit, except parts for compatibility with 16-bit applications, and only generic thunks were available to thunk from Win16 to Win32, as for Windows 95.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Platform SDK shipped with a compiler that could produce the code needed for these thunks.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Versions of 64-bit Windows are also able to run 32-bit applications via WoW64.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The SysWOW64 folder located in the Windows folder on the OS drive contains several tools to support 32-bit applications.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Each version of Microsoft Windows contains a version of Windows API, and almost every new version of Microsoft Windows has introduced additions and changes to the Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The name, Windows API, refers to essentially the same capability in each version of Windows, but there is another name for this capability that is based on major architectural aspects of the Windows version that contains it.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] When there was only one version, it was simply called Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Then, when the first major update was made, Microsoft gave it the name Win32 and gave the first version the name Win16.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The term Windows API refers to both versions and all subsequently developed major versions.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Wine project provides a Win32 API compatibility layer for Unix-like platforms, between Linux kernel API and programs written for the Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] ReactOS goes a step further and aims to implement the full Windows operating system, working closely with the Wine project to promote code re-use and compatibility.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] DosWin32 and HX DOS Extender are other projects which emulate the Windows API to allow executing simple Windows programs from a DOS command line.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Odin is a project to emulate Win32 on OS/2, superseding the original Win-OS/2 emulation which was based on Microsoft code.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Other minor implementations include the MEWEL and Zinc libraries which were intended to implement a subset of the Win16 API on DOS (see List of platform-independent GUI libraries).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Windows Interface Source Environment (WISE) was a licensing program from Microsoft which allowed developers to recompile and run Windows-based applications on Unix and Macintosh platforms.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] WISE SDKs were based on an emulator of the Windows API that could run on those platforms.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] To develop software that uses the Windows API, a compiler must be able to use the Microsoft-specific DLLs listed above (COM-objects are outside Win32 and assume a certain vtable layout).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The compiler must either handle the header files that expose the interior API function names, or supply such files.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] For the language C++, Zortech (later Symantec, then Digital Mars), Watcom and Borland have all produced well-known commercial compilers that have been used often with Win16, Win32s, and Win32.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Some of them supplied *memory extenders*, allowing Win32 programs to run on Win16 with Microsoft's redistributable Win32s DLL.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Zortech compiler was probably one of the first stable and usable C++ compilers for Windows programming, before Microsoft had a C++ compiler.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] For certain classes of applications, the compiler system should also be able to handle interface description language (IDL) files.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Collectively, these prerequisites (compilers, tools, libraries, and headers) are known as the *Microsoft Platform SDK*.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] As of 2016, the MinGW and Cygwin projects also provide such an environment based on the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), using a stand-alone header file set, to make linking against the Win32-specific DLLs simple.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] LCC-Win32 is a C compiler maintained by Jacob Navia, freeware for non-commercial use.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Pelles C is a freeware C compiler maintained by Pelle Orinius.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Free Pascal is a free software Object Pascal compiler that supports the Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The MASM32 package is a mature project providing support for the Windows API under Microsoft Macro Assembler (MASM) by using custom made or converted headers and libraries from the Platform SDK.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Flat assembler FASM allows building Windows programs without using an external linker, even when running on Linux.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Windows specific compiler support is also needed for Structured Exception Handling (SEH).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] This system serves two purposes: it provides a substrate on which language-specific exception handling can be implemented, and it is how the kernel notifies applications of exceptional conditions such as dereferencing an invalid pointer or stack overflow.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] The Microsoft/Borland C++ compilers had the ability to use this system as soon as it was introduced in Windows 95 and NT, however the actual implementation was undocumented and had to be reverse engineered for the Wine project and free compilers.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] SEH is based on pushing exception handler frames onto the stack, then adding them to a linked list stored in thread-local storage (the first field of the thread environment block).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] When an exception is thrown, the kernel and base libraries unwind the stack running handlers and filters as they are encountered.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Eventually, every exception unhandled by the application will be dealt with by the default backstop handler, which pops up the Windows common crash dialog.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Microsoft has plans to update the Windows API for modern C++ usage with their `win32metadata` project.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Currently, there is C++/WinRT and "Windows Implementation Library" (WIL) for doing this in modern C++.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-api] Microsoft has also created bindings for other languages, including C# and Rust for calling the Win32 API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT is not a runtime in a traditional sense but rather a language-independent application binary interface based on COM to allow object-oriented APIs to be consumed from multiple languages, with services usually provided by a full-blown runtime, such as type activation.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] That is, WinRT is an "API delivery system".
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Apps using the Windows Runtime may run inside a sandboxed environment to allow greater security and stability and can natively support both x86 and ARM.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT components are designed with interoperability among multiple languages and APIs in mind, including native, managed and scripting languages.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Built-in APIs provided by Windows which use the WinRT ABI are commonly known as WinRT APIs; however, anyone can use the WinRT ABI for their own APIs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT is implemented in the programming language C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Its underlying technology, the Windows API (Win32 API), is written mostly in the language C.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It is an unmanaged application binary interface based on Component Object Model (COM) that allows interfacing from multiple languages, as does COM.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] However, the API definitions are stored in `.winmd` files, which are encoded in ECMA 335 metadata format, which .NET Framework also uses with a few modifications.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] For WinRT components implemented in native code, the metadata file only contains the definition of methods, classes, interfaces and enumerations and the implementation is provided in a separate DLL.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] This common metadata format makes it easier to consume WinRT APIs from .NET apps with simpler syntax than P/Invoke.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Windows provides a set of built-in APIs which are built on the WinRT ABI which provide everything from the XAML-based WinUI library and device access such as camera, microphone, etc.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The Component Extensions of C++/CX are recommended for use at the API-boundary only, not for other purposes.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Regular C++ (with COM-specific discipline) can also be used to program with WinRT components, with the help of the Windows Runtime C++ Template Library (WRL), which is similar in purpose to what Active Template Library provides for COM.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In 2019, Microsoft deprecated C++/CX in favor of the C++/WinRT header library.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Most WinRT applications run within a sandbox and need explicit user approval to access critical OS features and underlying hardware.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] By default, file access is restricted to several predetermined locations, such as the directories Documents or Pictures.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT applications are packaged in the .appx and later the .msix file format; based upon Open Packaging Conventions, it uses a ZIP format with added XML files.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT applications are distributed mostly through an application store named Microsoft Store, where Windows apps (termed *Windows Store apps*) can be purchased and downloaded by users.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Initially, WinRT apps could only be sideloaded from outside Windows Store on Windows 8 or RT systems that are part of a Windows domain, or equipped with a special activation key obtained from Microsoft.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] However these restrictions were lifted in the Windows 10 November Update, where users can freely sideload any app signed with a trusted certificate by enabling a setting.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In a major departure from Win32 and similarly to .NET Framework 4.5, most APIs which are expected to take significant time to complete are implemented as asynchronous.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] When calling a Windows Runtime asynchronous function, the task is started on another thread or process and the function returns immediately, freeing the app to perform other tasks while waiting for results.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The asynchronous model requires new programming language constructs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Each language provides their own way to consume asynchronous APIs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Parts of the built-in API needing asynchronous access include on-screen messages and dialogs, file access, Internet connectivity, sockets, streams, devices and services, and calendar, contacts and appointments.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The metadata describes the APIs written using the WinRT ABI.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It defines a programming model that makes it possible to write object-oriented code that can be shared across programming languages, and enables services like reflective programming (reflection).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Herb Sutter, C++ expert at Microsoft, explained during his session on C++ at the 2011 Build conference that the WinRT metadata is in the same format as CLI metadata.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Native code (i.e., processor-specific machine code) cannot contain metadata, so it is stored in a separate metadata file that can be reflected like ordinary CLI assemblies.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Since it is the same format as CLI metadata, WinRT APIs can be used from managed CLI languages as if it was just a .NET API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT has a rich object-oriented class-based type system that is built on the metadata.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It supports constructs with corresponding constructs in the .NET framework: classes, methods, properties, delegates, and events.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] One of the major additions to WinRT relative to COM is the cross-application binary interface (ABI), .NET-style generics.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Only interfaces and delegates can be generic, runtime classes and methods in them can't.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Generic interfaces are also known as parameterized interfaces.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In C++/CX, they are declared using the keyword `generic` with a syntax very similar to that of keyword `template`.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT classes (ref classes) can also be genericized using C++ templates, but only template instantiations can be exported to .winmd metadata (with some name mangling), unlike WinRT generics which preserve their genericity in the metadata.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT also provides a set of interfaces for generic containers that parallel those in the C++ Standard Library, and languages provide some reciprocal (back-and-forth) conversion functions.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The consumption of WinRT collections in .NET languages (e.g., C# and VB) and in JavaScript is more transparent than in C++, with automated mappings into their natural equivalents occurring behind the scenes.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] When authoring a WinRT component in a managed language, some extra, COM-style rules must be followed, e.g. .NET framework collection types cannot be declared as return types, but only the WinRT interfaces that they implement can be used at the component boundary.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Classes that are compiled to target the WinRT are called *WinRT components*.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] They are classes that can be written in any supported language and for any supported platform.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] This metadata makes it possible to interface with the component from any other WinRT language.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The runtime requires WinRT components that are built with .NET Framework to use the defined interface types or .NET type interfaces, which automatically map to the first named.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Inheritance is as yet not supported in managed WinRT components, except for XAML classes.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Programs and libraries targeted for the WinRT runtime can be created and consumed from several platforms and programming languages.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Notably C/C++ (either with language extensions offering first-class support for WinRT concepts, or with a lower-level template library allowing to write code in standard C++), .NET (C# and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET)) and JavaScript.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Standard C++ is a *first-class citizen* of the WinRT platform.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] As of Windows 10, version 1803, the Windows SDK contains C++/WinRT.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] C++/WinRT is an entirely standard modern C++17 language projection for Windows Runtime (WinRT) APIs, implemented as a header-file-based library, and designed to provide first-class access to the modern Windows API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] With C++/WinRT, Windows Runtime APIs can be authored and consumed using any standards-compliant C++17 compiler.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT is a native platform and supports any native (and standard) C++ code, so that a C++ developer can reuse existing native C/C++ libraries.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] With C++/WinRT, there are no language extensions.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] There are two other legacy options for using WinRT from C++: Windows Runtime C++ Template Library (WRL), an ATL-style template library (similar to Windows Template Library or WTL), and C++/CX (C++ with Component Extensions) which resembles C++/CLI.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Because of the internal consumption requirements at Microsoft, WRL is exception-free, meaning its return-value discipline is HRESULT-based just like that of COM.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] C++/CX on the other hand wraps-up calls to WinRT with code that does error checking and throws exceptions as appropriate.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] C++/CX has several extensions that enable integration with the platform and its type system.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The syntax resembles the one of C++/CLI although it produces native (although not standard) code and metadata that integrates with the runtime.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] For example, WinRT objects may be allocated with `ref new`, which is the counterpart of `gcnew` from C++/CLI.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The hat operator `^` retains its meaning, however in the case where both the caller and callee are written in C++ and living in the same process, a hat reference is simply a pointer to a vptr to a virtual method table (vtable, VMT).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Along with C++/CX, relative to traditional C++ COM programming, are partial classes, again inspired by .NET.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] These allow instance WinRT XAML code to be translated into C++ code by tools, and then combined with human-written code to produce the complete class while allowing clean separation of the machine-generated and human-edited parts of a class implementation into different files.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The .NET Framework and the Common Language Runtime (CLR) are integrated into the WinRT as a subplatform.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It has influenced and set the standards for the ecosystem through the metadata format and libraries.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The CLR provides services like JIT-compilation code and garbage collection.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT applications using .NET languages use the XAML-based WinUI, and are primarily written in C#, VB.NET, and for the first time for XAML, with native code using C++/CX.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Although not yet officially supported, programs can also be written in other .NET languages.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] With .NET 5, Microsoft removed the built-in WinRT support and instead created CsWinRT, a tool that generates interop code for accessing Windows Runtime APIs similar to how C++/WinRT works.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Classes defined in WinRT components that are built in managed .NET languages must be declared as `sealed`, so they cannot be derived from.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] However, non-sealed WinRT classes defined elsewhere can be inherited from in .NET, their virtual methods overridden, and so on; but the inherited managed class must still be sealed.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Members that interface with another language must have a signature with WinRT types or a managed type that is convertible to these.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT applications can also be coded using HTML with JavaScript in code-behind, which are run using the Trident rendering engine and Chakra JavaScript engine, both of which are also used by Internet Explorer.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] When coding a WinRT app in JavaScript, its features are adapted to follow JavaScript naming conventions, and namespaces are also mapped to JavaScript objects.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Microsoft is in the process of projecting WinRT APIs to languages other than C++.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] One example is Rust/WinRT, an interface for programs written in Rust to consume and author WinRT APIs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Rust/WinRT is part of Windows App SDK (formerly Project Reunion), a Microsoft effort to reconcile traditional Windows desktop and the UWP app model.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] With the introduction of the Universal Windows Platform (UWP), the platform has received many API bridges that allow programs originally developed for other platforms to be ported easily while taking advantage of UWP features.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Microsoft has provided bridges for Android (defunct since 2016), iOS (Cocoa Touch), Progressive Web Apps, Silverlight, as well as traditional Windows desktop apps (using MSIX packaging from the Windows App SDK).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] WinRT comes with an application programming interface (API) in the form of a class library that exposes the features of Windows 8 for the developer, like its immersive interface API.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It is accessible and consumable from any supported language.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The Windows Runtime classes is a set SDKs that provide access to all functionality from the XAML parser to the camera function.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The SDKs are implemented as native C/C++ libraries (unmanaged).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The naming conventions for the components (classes and other members) in the API are heavily influenced by the .NET naming conventions which uses camel case (specifically PascalCase).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Microsoft recommends users to follow these rules in case where no others are given.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] These conventions are projected differently in some languages, like JavaScript, which converts it to its conventions and the other way around.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] This is to give a native and consistent experience regardless of the programming language.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Since Windows Runtime is projected to various languages, some restrictions on fundamental data types exist so as to host all such languages.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Programmers must be careful with the behavior of those types when used with public access (for method parameters, method return values, properties, etc.).
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In .NET languages and C++, a rich set of data types exists, representing various numerals.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] can only represent up to 53 bits of precision.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In WinRT, the only lacking numeral data type is 8-bit signed integer relative to .NET and C++.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] JavaScript developers must be careful when dealing with big numbers while coding for WinRT.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Strings are immutable in .NET and JavaScript, but mutable in C++.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In .NET and C++, structs are value types, and such a struct can contain any type in it.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] JavaScript does not directly support structs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In WinRT, use of structs is allowed only for containing types that have value semantics, including numerals, strings, and other structs.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Pointers or interface references are disallowed.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In .NET, objects are passed by reference, whereas numerals and structs are passed by value.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In C++, all types can be passed by reference or value.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In WinRT, interfaces are passed by reference; all other types can be passed either by value or by reference.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In .NET, C++, and JavaScript arrays are reference types.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In WinRT, arrays are value types and quite restricted.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] property is used to subscribe to events.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In WinRT, all languages can use their own way to subscribe to events.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Some .NET collections map directly to WinRT collections.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] type resembles arrays and the array syntax is used to consume them.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] type is a key/value pair collection, and is projected as Dictionary in .NET languages.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] .NET and C++ also support overloading on type.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] In WinRT, only parameter number is used for overloading.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] All WinRT methods are designed such that any method taking longer than 50 milliseconds is an async method.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] For the full runtime library, all methods that have a chance to last longer than 50 ms are implemented as asynchronous methods only.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Windows Phone 8.1 uses a version of the Windows Runtime named the *Windows Phone Runtime*.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It enables developing applications in C# and VB.NET, and Windows Runtime components in C++/CX.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Although WP8 brought limited support, the platform did eventually converge with Windows 8.1 in Windows Phone 8.1.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Windows Phone 8 has limited support for developing and consuming Windows Runtime components through *Windows Phone Runtime*.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Many of the Windows Runtime APIs in Windows 8 that handle core operating system functions have been ported to Windows Phone 8.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Support for developing native games using C++/CX and DirectX has been added, by request from the game development industry.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] However, the Windows Phone XAML Framework is still based on the same Microsoft Silverlight framework, as in Windows Phone 7, for backward compatibility.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Thus, as of 2016, XAML development is impossible in C++/CX.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Development using either HTML5 or WinJS is unsupported on Windows Phone 8.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Windows Runtime support on Windows Phone 8.1 converges with Windows 8.1.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The release brings a full Windows Runtime API to the platform, including support for WinRT XAML, and language bindings for C++/CX, and HTML5-JavaScript.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] There is also a project type called *Universal apps* to enable apps to share code across 8.1 versions of Windows Phone and Windows.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] The Windows Phone 8 Silverlight Framework has been updated.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] It can exploit some of the new features in the Windows Runtime.
[src:uwp-apps/windows-runtime] Windows Phone Runtime uses the AppX package format from Windows 8, after formerly using Silverlight XAP.
